We're going to stop working on image classification and instead try out a new task that still use images: semantic segmentation. As always, the best way to describe things in deep learning is by specifying the exact inputs and ouputs. So...

Essentially, for a given input image, we want to "color" or assign a class label to every pixel in it.

Previously, when we did image classification, the input was an image, and the output was a single class label. Here, we have an input image again, but the output is a class label for each pixel in the input image. In other words, the output is another image where the color of the pixels twll us what's in that region of the image.

{% raw %} 
from fastai.vision.all import *
{% endraw %}

Prepare Dataset

For segmentation, we're going to use a dataset called CAMVID, which is a collection of common scenes that you might expect a self-driving car, for example, to see. Note that we're not going to level 5 autonomy just yet, but it's a step..

CAMVID is available directly in fastai, so we're going to load it in the usual way.

{% raw %} 
path = untar_data(URLs.CAMVID)
{% endraw %}

As an aside, the reason we're using all these common, standard, academic datasets is not because they're representative of the real world. It's because these datasets, like CIFAR10, ImageNet, and CAMVID, are the ones that researchers have agreed to use, so we have a common standard for comparing and benchmarkig models.

The CAMVID dataset is also formatted differently, so we'll have to do a little more work to get it into the format we want (a fastai DataLoaders object).

One problem is that the list of images and labels are not in order, so they don't correspond to one another. We need a function that gives us the path to the mask that matches the right image.

{% raw %} 
def get_mask(filename):
    return path/'labels'/f'{filename.stem}_P{filename.suffix}'
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
img = PILImage.create(images[0])
mask = PILMask.create(get_mask(images[0]))
img.show(figsize=(5,5))
mask.show(figsize=(5,5), alpha=1)

Notice that the type of this tensor is an integer. That's because each pixel corresponds to a single class, which is a discrete variable. But looking at a bunch of numbers like this doesn't tell us much. What exactly does a "4" mean?

{% raw %} 
codes = np.loadtxt(path/'codes.txt', dtype=str); codes

{% endraw %}

Well, the CAMVID dataset also provides a list of "codes" in a text file, which show us how to map those integers to specific classes that are human-interpretable.

Assemble DataLoaders

Before creating the DataLoaders, let's set it up in a way that passes the images through at half their original size. This makes training faster, but is also important for another really cool technique that we'll look at in a moment.

{% raw %} 
full_size = mask.shape
full_size

(720, 960)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
half_size = (360, 480)
{% endraw %}

We now have everything we need to assemble our DataLoaders.

Remeber, fastai classes and functions are super generic and flexible, so we can use both the techniques we used previously (transfer learning and data augmentation) together in the same waywe did before!

{% raw %} 
data = DataBlock(blocks = (ImageBlock, MaskBlock(codes)),
                 get_items = get_image_files,
                 splitter = FileSplitter(path/'valid.txt'),
                 get_y = get_mask,
                 batch_tfms = [*aug_transforms(size=half_size), Normalize.from_stats(*imagenet_stats)]
                )
{% endraw %}

In particular, take a look at the usage of aug_transforms from week 2, which we used for data augmentation, and Normalize.from_stats(*imagenet_stats) from week 1, which we used for transfer learning. These functions are written in the exact same way as they were for the previous lessons (go and take a look if you want).

{% raw %} 
dls = data.dataloaders(path/'images', bs=8)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
dls.show_batch(figsize=(20, 8))
{% endraw %}

You might be used to batch sizes of 64+ from image classification, but that doesn't work here. Since the output is much larger, training these segmentation networks usually requires much more memory, so we have to considerably reduce the batch size.

There are a few more things we need to take care of to ensure that we get resonable and interpretable outputs.

{% raw %} 
dls.vocab = codes
name2id = {v:k for k,v in enumerate(codes)}
void_code = name2id['Void']
{% endraw %}

Specifically, we want to make sure that we don't count the "unknown" or "void" class when we compute accuracy (this is how the CAMVID accuracy is defined, and you'll see that it makes a difference).

{% raw %} 
def camvid_accuracy(pred, real):
    real = real.squeeze(1)
    mask = real != void_code
    return (pred.argmax(dim=1)[mask] == real[mask]).float().mean()
{% endraw %}

UNet Learner & The Small Things That Make A Difference

So far, we've been using a cnn_learner (a convolutional neural network). This is good for things like classification or regression on images, for which you're reducing the input image to something simple like a few numbers or a class prediction.

But for segmentation, we're going to use something else. This time, we're swapping a cnn_learner out for a unet_learner. This is a different type of architecure that was actually originally proposed as a model for medical imaging. But it turns out that it performs extremely well for most segmentation tasks across domains.

The fastai version of this is a dynamic unet. It's "dynamic" because we can use almost any architecture, and fast will automatically convert it into a unet-style model for us.

But there are a few other things we're going to add on top of that...

{% raw %} 
config = unet_config(self_attention=True, act_cls=Mish)
learn = unet_learner(dls, resnet18, metrics=[camvid_accuracy], config=config, opt_func=ranger)
{% endraw %}

There's a handy function that tells up what's going on with our model. It can be useful when you're analyze your architecture before training.

Now, instead of using the default fine_tune() call as we did last time, let's use a tool called the learning rate finder to pick a good learning rate specfic to our model, dataset, and loss function.

{% raw %} 
learn.lr_find()

SuggestedLRs(lr_min=0.00036307806149125097, lr_steep=0.0008317637839354575)
{% endraw %}

It seems like 1e-3 might be a good choice. We now train in the usual way with an additional lr parameter in the fine_tune() function.

{% raw %} 
lr = 1e-3

Progressize Resizing

Now, let's try something that might help up get do a little better. Remeber that we trained on half-sized images? Well, let's upscale now and fine-tune the model again.

{% raw %} 
data_full = DataBlock(blocks = (ImageBlock, MaskBlock(codes)),
                      get_items = get_image_files,
                      splitter = FileSplitter(path/'valid.txt'),
                      get_y = get_mask,
                      batch_tfms = [*aug_transforms(size=full_size), Normalize.from_stats(*imagenet_stats)]
                )
{% endraw %}

Since we quadrupled the number of pixels, we should shrink our batch size down to avoid CUDA out-of-memory errors.

{% raw %} 
dls_full = data_full.dataloaders(path/"images", bs=1)
dls_full.vocab = codes
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
learn_full = unet_learner(dls, resnet18, metrics=[camvid_accuracy], config=config, opt_func=ranger)
learn_full.load('resnet18_half.pkl');
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
learn_full.lr_find()
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
lr = 1e-3
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
learn_full.fine_tune(10, lr, freeze_epochs=5)
